The Voice is an American singing competition television series broadcast on NBC. It premiered during the spring television cycle on April 26, 2011, and expanded into the fall cycle with the premiere of the third season on September 10, 2012. Based on the original The Voice of Holland, and part of The Voice franchise it has aired seventeen seasons and aims to find currently unsigned singing talent (solo or duets, professional and amateur) contested by aspiring singers, age 13 or over, drawn from public auditions.
The winner is determined by television viewers voting by telephone, Internet, SMS text, and iTunes Store purchases of the audio-recorded artists' vocal performances. They receive US$100,000 and a record deal with Universal Music Group for winning the competition. The winners of the sixteen seasons have been Javier Colon, Jermaine Paul, Cassadee Pope, Danielle Bradbery, Tessanne Chin, Josh Kaufman, Craig Wayne Boyd, Sawyer Fredericks, Jordan Smith, Alisan Porter, Sundance Head, Chris Blue, Chloe Kohanski, Brynn Cartelli, Chevel Shepherd, Maelyn Jarmon, and Todd Tilghman, respectively.

The end of the frontier was a phrase used by Frederick Jackson Turner in his 1893 essay The Significance of the Frontier in American History to describe the claim that the availability of free land in the 19th century was a major factor in the transformation of American democracy and society. In his essay, Turner argued that the American frontier established a process of development that gave American democracy its character and identity. The idea of the frontier was important to American national identity, and the frontier thesis was promoted by generations of scholars to explain the characteristics of the American people and their institutions.
The frontier thesis was one of the earliest scholarly interpretations and remains one of the most influential ones. Turner's ideas persist in scholarship, and recent historians have combined the thesis with other interpretations, such as the importance of slavery to the American economy, the role of class in American politics, and the importance of the existence of a state in the development of American industry.
Turner's frontier thesis was a significant development in the historiography of the United States.
